data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already didn't natively support sync operations — it performed **sync-over-async** (blocking on async calls internally). You opted into this with a configuration like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousQueryExecution(true));
```

**In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four of your sync calls — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

### The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The async LINQ methods live in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` (ensure `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;`).
- `Add()` itself stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory. The actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- This change will ripple up your call chain — callers must also become `async`/`await` all the way to the controller action (which ASP.NET Core already supports natively).
